–Male":"1073–Afdød","1075–Male":"1075–Afdød","1012–Male":"1012–Afdød","about 1072":"omkring 1072","about 1073":"omkring 1073","about 1070":"omkring 1070","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","1073":"1073","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1068":"1068","1012":"1012","1100":"1100","4 April 1068":"4. april 1068","about 1075":"omkring 1075","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"1040–":"1040–Overleden","1040–Male":"1040–Overleden","1050–Female":"1050–Overleden","1068–1100":"1068–1100","1070–Male":"1070–Overleden","1072–Male":"1072–Overleden","1073–Male":"1073–Overleden","1075–Male":"1075–Overleden","1012–Male":"1012–Overleden","about 1072":"circa 1072","about 1073":"circa 1073","about 1070":"circa 1070","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","1073":"1073","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1068":"1068","1012":"1012","1100":"1100","4 April 1068":"4 april 1068","about 1075":"circa 1075","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1040–":"1040–Deceased","1040–Male":"1040–Deceased","1050–Female":"1050–Deceased","1068–1100":"1068–1100","1070–Male":"1070–Deceased","1072–Male":"1072–Deceased","1073–Male":"1073–Deceased","1075–Male":"1075–Deceased","1012–Male":"1012–Deceased","about 1072":"about 1072","about 1073":"about 1073","about 1070":"about 1070","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","1073":"1073","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1068":"1068","1012":"1012","1100":"1100","4 April 1068":"4 April 1068","about 1075":"about 1075","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maunsell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Irish:  see  Mansell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mansell","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands):","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Old French <i>mansel</i> ‘inhabitant of Le Mans or the surrounding area of Maine’. The place was originally named in Latin <i>(ad) Ceromannos</i>, from the name of the Gaulish tribe living there, the <i>Ceromanni</i>. The name was shortened to <i>Celmans</i> and then became <i>Le Mans</i> as a result of the mistaken identification of the first syllable with the Old French demonstrative adjective.","status name for a particular type of feudal tenant, Anglo-Norman French <i>mansel</i>, one who occupied a <i>manse</i> (from Late Latin <i>mansa</i> ‘dwelling’), a measure of land sufficient to support one family."]}]},{"name":"Philippe","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Philip</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Philip","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":26,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":46,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":56,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":66,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Philippe Maunsell was born in 1040, in Normandy, France as the son of Henri De Le Mans. He had at least 5 sons with Agnes Demoiselle de Montsorrel. In 1066, at the age of 26, his occupation is listed as cupbearer to william the conqueror and accompanied him to england. He died in Buckinghamshire, England."},"et":{"1040–":"1040–Surnud","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1068–1100":"1068–1100","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","1072–Male":"1072–Surnud","1073–Male":"1073–Surnud","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1012–Male":"1012–Surnud","about 1072":"umbes 1072","about 1073":"umbes 1073","about 1070":"umbes 1070","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1040":"1040","1073":"1073","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1068":"1068","1012":"1012","1100":"1100","4 April 1068":"4. aprill 1068","about 1075":"umbes 1075","Buckinghamshire, England